{"type":"message","id":"714589dc","parentId":"ad2e1fc0","timestamp":"2026-03-26T17:27:43.593Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The MediaCrawler MCP search didn't return anything useful. It seems like the crawl_search doesn't return data inline but rather writes it to a file, and we need to poll for completion.\n\nLet me try a different approach - use the小红书 MCP that's already running (port 18060) and try to get the list_feeds and then check if we can navigate to search results. Actually wait - port 18060's小红书 MCP had list_feeds which gives the homepage. It doesn't have search.\n\nActually, let me try a completely different approach. Let me use the小红书 MCP with the cookie from the browser session. The browser opened xiaohongshu.com and we saw a login page. But I might be able to use the existing xiaohongshu cookie if Chrome has cookies stored. But browser profile didn't work because Chrome wasn't running.\n\nWait actually the browser DID work at some point earlier - I was able to open a browser tab. But Chrome wasn't running so it couldn't attach to the existing browser.\n\nActually the issue is simpler: Chrome is not running so I can't use profile=\"user\" to attach. And the standalone OpenClaw browser doesn't have the user's logged-in state.\n\nLet me just be honest - both MCPs have issues:\n1. 小红书 MCP (port 18060): No search tool, only homepage feeds\n2. MediaCrawler MCP (port 18080): Search tool returns but doesn't actually return results inline, just \"Accepted\"\n\nThe MediaCrawler stores results in files. Let me check what store_type options exist and if there's a way to get results synchronously.\n\nActually, the README for MediaCrawler MCP mentions it uses json store_type by default. The crawl_search is async - it accepts the job and stores results. Let me check if there's a file-based result I can read after running the search.\n\nLet me check the data directory more carefully."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_